Jun Wee I was scammed by two four-flushers in a single day of using Uber in Singapore. Never had I had an issue using Uber in other countries!  Our driver, Michelle tampered with the journey details and entered her own home address to bump up the original charges.   She accidentally told us she was going home and it was her last ride for the day.  Lo and behold, in my Uber receipt the end destination was Yishun instead of where I live which was entered in the Uber app when I first made a booking.  The driver also tampered with the records - the mileage was changed to reflect a journey of 3.2 kilometres apparently driven in 01:12:17.   This is a serious criminal offence and this con-artist should be permanently banned from commercial driving.  To make things worse, there is no actual customer service personnel to follow-up over such negative issues. Unlike ComfortDelGro Taxi which has a dedicated manager to call up customers when they face serious issues with their drivers.  Uber only sends affected customers generic computerized messages that do not contain any detail on how the driver is dealt with. In some cases, the driver is still allowed to continue driving despite taking advantage of Uber or its customers.

We were alerted that our driver would arrive in 25 minutes and assumed it was incorrect as the GPS showed that the car was at the airport terminal we were at.  5 minutes later, we discovered that the driver was at Bedok south road and was completing a trip! By that time, it was too late to cancel our booking.   In the car, he received a call from a passenger who was also like us, waiting at the airport.   This dishonest driver who is obviously accepting calls at the airport just after he picks up passengers at the same location is unscrupulous and should be removed from Uber.

Uber!!!! And all new customers. Please take note and be careful when using the discount code of uber.    I m so upset and disappointed for my first experience in taking uber ride.  This will be my first and last that I ever have with uber.  My Friend has given me a discount code for taking first timer ride in uber. For the discount is great, despite many ppl told me that the fare, the driver, the apps and even the customer service are bad, don ever consider about using uber. I ignore them as I want to give uber a chance and as an alternative to get a ride beside my usual ride from Grab.    I regretted!!! I wrote to uber and was Told that the code is not valid and I asked why there is no decline of the code during booking, no reply from them anymore.    I m writing this post to warn others not to take uber when you are new, the fare is double of grab, I checked grab n uber app this morning, grab only quoted the fare $15, whereas uber quoted $25.  Uber just needed to cheat all for all the one time charge and will forgo all customers for not returning to them.  Uber nvr thought of retaining customers for good, go for grab instead, the customer service will go all the way to help you and compensate for their mistakes and not to lose you, grab even give loyalty discount for using grab.  So all customers, just be careful if u r using uber!!!!

I am lodging a complaint on the unprofessional and threatening behaviour of one of your drivers.   The driver arrived at Ikea pick-up point on the second lane, and barely stopped at the uphill slope. I had two heavy Ikea bags and gestured for him to move forward as cars were coming in and it would be difficult to load the bags into the boot. He did not move his car. I waited for a taxi to go past as it was coming up the slope and the taxi driver had impatiently honked at another driver ahead before I crossed over and loaded the boot.   I got into the car without saying a word. The driver asked if I was happy with the service. I replied, 'Not particularly' (along this line). He then asked me to get out of the car and stated he would not drive me to my destination. I assure you if this sounds absurd and unbelievable, it happened exactly as I have described. The driver's car ought to have a video recording; feel free to verify that what I am relating is the absolute truth.  This driver was most determined at provoking me. I told him I would not do as he pleases. He then said he would drive me to the police station. I told him to do what he needed to do. He then drove around the Ikea drop-off point a number of times before calling the police on his mobile phone.   On the phone with the police, he stated that he was on the second lane because Uber drivers are not supposed to pick up at taxi stands. He then added that I was well aware of this. We had zero exchange on this, so it is perplexing that the driver would know what was in my head. It became apparent the driver had to lie to justify his absurd behaviour.  The driver was most selfish to throw this fracas, especially since he had picked up another Uberpool rider and so he was being most unprofessional and inconveniencing two riders at once. Please check with the the other rider if I had said a word upon entering the car. At no point during this incident did I rant, rave or even raise my voice and hurl verbal abuse. The driver is not the owner of me that he should think he can dictate my feelings, thoughts or actions. It is not as if he had greeted me politely and I had not responded. It is not as if he had graciously helped with my bags and I had been ungrateful. Even so, the driver should not feel at liberty to treat riders with so much disdain and disrespect at his fancy, especially when he is representing the Uber brand.  I called √úber and connected with Christine and John, a supervisor, who stated there was nothing he could do to assist, while waiting for the police to arrive. It is most absurd that the police had to be called in, when I had done absolutely nothing to provoke the driver. Basically, the driver imagines riders who enter a car quietly ought to be treated badly, humiliated, and terrorised.   Threatening a passenger and asking her to get out of the car as a means to humiliate her when she had said absolutely nothing cannot possibly be acceptable behaviour of Uber drivers or be representative of Uber's standard.  Inspector Lau informed me that it was really unsafe for me to continue with this journey. I agreed. I got another ride, not with Uber.  Uber needs to do the right thing here and take heed of my complaint. This was most unacceptable and absurd service in this day and age. I will state the likes of such drivers will only tarnish the Uber brand. Kindly ensure that this matter receives the attention it deserves. Think it is the time to put to a stop this 1.35 and toddler issue or over capacity. Is all about contractual agreements between riders with UG and UG with drivers.  1) Contract between UG and Riders, is for UG to get the right car type to send rider from point A to B, but has UG done enough in rider booking app to ensure riders declare the mix of people taking the car? Since LTA and TP has such requirements, there is no wrong on UG to force riders to declare since is it a electronic service contract and the contract has to cover the drivers providing the service. Drivers has no contact and idea who are the riders before the booking and picking the riders, only UG has the mean to contact rider between themselves, more can be done before UG accepts rider's request and sending to drivers.  2) Contract between UG and drivers, is for drivers to fulfill jobs from UG to send their clients (riders) from point A to B. Right now drivers has zero ideas the mix riders they are picking until pickups, drivers should have the option to cancel the trip if the rider's mix is not as per LTA and TP requirements that cancellation should not impact their rating or incentives.  I am proposing that on rider's app, they have to declare if their rider mix has passenger below 1.35m and toddlers, if riders never declare but has such mix, the electronic service contract is consider null and void that driver's app should have the option to cancel without the fear of affecting their rating or incentives. In such cases, since driver already reached pick location and only to realize that riders falsely declared their rider mix, they can start the trip and end with special option indicating false rider declaration that a fee can be charged on rider for trip made to pick them. This will prevent riders from trying to book another car by falsely declaring rider mix.  Right now UG is making drivers or riders to communicate on LTA/TP requirements that has resulted in sour situations in who to cancel the trip if car cannot take the rider. All these are nonsenses, under the PHV new framework, UG has not done enough on ensuring right service to riders and riders both should be fined to if they insist on boarding a car that resulting in drivers caught breaking rules, else where is driver protection?

There were 3 rides that I took, upfront fare was a certain amount. The fare was BEFORE discount, and the discount was supposed to be applied after the ride. I know this because for so many of the rides I have taken, the discount only got applied AFTER the ride. However, on these 3 particular rides, at the end of the rides, the fare became at least $5 to $6 MORE than the original fare I was initially shown.   I then contacted Uber regarding the fare being bloated after the ride - and guess what?? They adjusted the fare down to the original upfront fare, but CLAIMED that the bloated fare WAS the original fare, and hence, I did not get the discounts from the original upfront fare because that was supposed to be the discounted fare. Does that even make sense?? How can a fare be bloated up instead of getting discounted, at the end of a ride??   Morever, I took screenshots from various other rides I took during the same period, as well as noted ALL my evening rides - ALL these rides only had discount applied AFTER the ride! So, is Uber trying to cheat our money by doing this? Out of 20 rides, all upfront fare is original price, then slip 3 rides in and bloat the fare "by mistake" after the ride, then CLAIM that that was in fact, the original fare and the original upfront fare was the discounted fare??? I wouldn't have booked if I knew!  One particuler Uber operator, Naresh, was clearly lying!

Dear Uber  You've been changing your promotion code discount application rules for Singapore these past months.  Before (Jan to March), it was last in first out (LIFO) and on Thursday evenings when we received and input the new promotion code sent to us via email, our currently active promotion code (sometimes not fully utilised, eg only used 2/4 eligibility) would cease to work and we'd need to wait till Thursday midnight or Friday 6am to again get to enjoy our new promo code discount. There was also no simultaneous application like now for RIDEMORN and DAYRIDE (only one promotion code can be used at a time). Previously it would be one or the other depending on which we input first. We'd need to exhaust 4 trips (eg. RIDEMORN) with one before the other (DAYRIDE) would kick in.  Then in April, suddenly you got very liberal and changed the rules for Singapore to highest discount applies. We were also allowed to stack different promo code discounts like LiveUp $10 with say a $5 off (nett $15 off on our 10th LiveUp trips. Trips with $0 fares plus promo discounted fares towards the 9 LiveUp trip count. Fares with both the discount value (eg $5 off) were applied first then percentage discount (eg 50%) was applied to the remainder and fare charged; listed as Discount ($5 off) and Promotion (50% off amount). Also we were literally covered for promo code discounts from 12-6am, 6-10am and 10am to 12pm. EVERYONE WAS SUPER HAPPY AND CONTENT. Uber usage was very high.  NOW I HEAR THAT THIS WEEK, without ANY WARNING or NOTICE whatsoever, Uber in Singapore had regressed back to LIFO‚ÅâÔ∏èüò°üò°üò° You've caught many Uber riders off guard. How? You've "kindly" given selected riders with 4 x $3 off, 20-50% off (customised) promotion codes. By accepting them, they're no longer eligible for RIDEMORN, DAYRIDE or NIGHTRIDES. They'll need to use their active promo code or exhaust their eligibility. BACK TO THE STONE AGES again‚ÄºÔ∏èüò°üò°üò° What the heck are you trying to do? Screw with your loyal riders in such a cruel and unscrupulous manner‚ÅâÔ∏èü§î Why mess with a good thing that was working fine to everyone's satisfaction‚ÅâÔ∏èü§îüò°üò°üò°  This week, I've received a large number of complaints from my almost 9,500 FB members (https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/) with angry complaints about usage and application of promo code discounts; along with improper LiveUp trip counter (not moving and should be entitled to their $10 off but denied due to insufficient trip count or "can't be combined with other promos.")  Things are seriously getting screwed up on your end when you're giving your customers surprises and conflicting replies. Please get all your foreign call centres' CSOs on the same page and give us all correct and consistent replies and the same and proper treatment. Their training and replies reflects very badly on Uber as a very disorganised company where "the left hand doesn't talk to the right hand." Total confusion and disharmony‚ÄºÔ∏è  Oh yes, with 9,500 members, IT IS VERY EASY to compare all your CSOs inconsistent and wrong replies. Get your act together please and ensure all your call centres are reading from the same rule book, ACTUALLY READ our message PROPERLY and THOROUGHLY, before just sending a "canned reply" that isn't even relevant to the issue/query.  Last, please read through your own online published LiveUp T&C (https://help.uber.com/h/afddb3fd-5907-4609-b9e7-43b6aa1aaa54) and SHOW US in A FB POST where it's says $0 trips aren't a trip as in "take 9 trips) and when trips aren't counted due to use with promotion code discounts. I CHALLENGE YOU to reply my comment in full and don't even dare to ask me to email you as all my issues are a consolidation of all my all my FB group members' complaints. I'm very sure even non members have these same problems and issues.  Admin and Founder Uber/Grab Singapore Riders and Drivers Sharing. https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/

There was also no simultaneous application like now for RIDEMORN and DAYRIDE (only one promotion code can be used at a time). Previously it would be one or the other depending on which we input first. We'd need to exhaust 4 trips (eg. RIDEMORN) with one before the other (DAYRIDE) would kick in.  Then in April, suddenly you got very liberal and changed the rules for Singapore to highest discount applies. We were also allowed to stack different promo code discounts like LiveUp $10 with say a $5 off (nett $15 off on our 10th LiveUp trips. Trips with $0 fares plus promo discounted fares towards the 9 LiveUp trip count. I would like to highlight my disappointment with my recent Uber experience.  For background, when using Uber promotional codes, the upfront fare reflected on my Uber application has always been without the promotion value applied. On my latest trip applying the SAVEFIVE code, I only realised after seeing the receipt that the upfront fare had already incorporated the discount after applying promotional code (i.e. I paid $5 more than I expected).  I wrote in to Uber support to check on this issue, and had I been told that the upfront fare will always reflect the fare after incorporating the promotional value, that would be the end of the story. Instead, the response given was that sometimes the upfront fare incorporates the promotional value, sometimes it doesn‚Äôt, but don‚Äôt worry because the correct fare will be reflected in your receipt (see screenshot). This suspenseful game of Uber promotional code roulette speaks of a lack of transparency on fares and a principled approach on how promotional fares are reflected in the upfront fare. It‚Äôs like going to a restaurant which offering a promotional discount, but not knowing whether the discount applies until after you‚Äôve been presented with the bill. All Uber riders, please note for your future trips.  To add salt to an already gaping wound, the driver‚Äôs driving was erratic and hazardous (straddling between two lanes for more than a few seconds and coming without centimeters of hitting another car) and due to the questionable UberPool pairing algorithm, my journey (which would have taken 25 minutes by public transport and 6 times cheaper) took a grand total of 40 minutes. Had I known that I was paying a premium for inconvenience, dangerous driving and a longer journey, I might have considered keeping my money in my pocket for this trip.

My answer is C!! :)   uberPOOL pairs riders based on their destinations and routes.  uberPOOL allows riders likes us to benefit from lower prices due to economy of scale from riders sharing the same route. My answer is it depends!!!! But as the question is set without limit, I will assume all Uber rides are available and choose C! I.e. 6. Here's why...   For UberPOOL you can bring 1 more friend. i.e. max 2   For UberX you can bring up to 4 riders including yourself. i.e. max 4  For UberXL you can bring up to 6 riders including yourself, i.e. max 6  :)

The answer is C, 6! The person who requests the ride can invite other riders to split the fare with. Since the maximum number of people you can take an Uber with (boarding together as friends) is 6 (i.e. UberXL), the answer should be 6 too! Of course, for fewer number of riders like UberPool, the answer is probably 2.  However, the splitting of fares may fail sometimes as the other riders must accept your invitation for splitting if fare before the trip ends! If they do not accept or do not have a valid payment method, then this will fail and you will still be charged for their share! Ervin Lee

Answer: C. Driver's contact number  Uber implemented its number-masking technology that will "disguise" personal numbers so Singapore Uber drivers who call from their mobile devices will not be able to see the customer's mobile number and vice versa.  Instead, they will automatically be routed through an encrypted number.  Drivers and riders will then communicate through "dummy" numbers, essentially a forwarding number, designed to block the true caller IDs of both the driver and passenger.

C. The colour of the car will be shown on the screen, and license plate has always been shown to increase accountability.  The personal number of the driver is never shown as the call goes through call masking. Brilliant feature to protect the identity of both rider and driver.

So, taxi companies want to change to dynamic pricing for app bookings to compete head to head with Uber and Grab eh? It's still unclear if they'll only do it during their non peak (no surcharge applied) periods or 24/7? However it seems for street hails and taxi queues, the taxis will use metered fares. If they follow UG's booking fixed fare models, they could start off with GrabCar Economy and UberX like fixed fare trip bookings. If ambitious, they can even progress to a GrabShare and UberPool fixed trip option.  They could also offer promo codes to gain market share from Uber Ang Grab, kicking off another free for all promo code war. ComfortDelGro recently have already been announcing promo codes regularly and with their deep pockets. Combined with Premier and TransCab, this formidable taxi alliance or cartel combined could possibly outlast both Uber and Grab in a no holds bar price/promo code war. Uber and Grab have already slowed down their promo codes to a crawl and dripping trickle. Can Uber and Grab survive the onslaught of the combined taxi alliance/cartel? They may be even forced to form an unlikely and unholy alliance to fend off the competition from the new taxi juggernaut and be completely steamrolled!  Worst is taxis will have the best competitive advantage or ace in the whole of all. Taxis will be able to pickup adults with children under 1.35m as they have a LTA exemption. Good news for Uber and Grab drivers' headaches with those class of riders, plus these class of riders themselves not having to fear being rejected.  But the added competition for normal rides will become more fierce given the sheer size of the combined ComfortDelGro, Premier and TransCab (for now with HDT and SMRT waiting in the wings). Will Uber and Grab be able to handle the onslaught of the new monolith?  Drivers may defect on masse together with fare sensitive riders who have no brand loyalty. It could be an unexpected windfall for both as well as the taxi alliance with their many empty taxis gathering dust in their parking lot. The only barrier for drivers will be the taxi vocational driving license (TDVL). They were all set to take the PDVL (private) but may rethink TVDL now and need longer to obtain it than a PDVL. Existing taxi drivers who jumped ship to Uber or Grab will be able to transition back more easily. Those taxi drivers who were considering a move would probably stay out for now and have a wait and see perspective.  One thing is for sure. More likely than not it will be the rider who will once again be "king" and in the cat bird seat!   Time will tell who drivers will ultimately gravitate to. It's time for Uber and Grab to soon reassess many things like revising their partners' compensation, incentives, possibly personal welfare too like offering medical benefits for a start. They'll need to also reexamine their rider retention with lower fares and capped surges like in the Philippines, a new promo code strategy and ways to add value.   Grab has the obvious edge having diversified into so many other ventures. But how much it'll add to their bottom line, no one knows. Clearly it's up to Uber now to do more planning and strategising as they're clearly at the most disadvantage. Hopefully they will finally be forced to offer a customer service phone hotline, something they've long resisted and riders have been clamouring for.  It is going to be an extremely interesting couple of months to come. With the impending regulatory changes to PHV drivers and companies on top of the looming new form of fare competition, riders will be licking their lips with anticipation of being spoilt for choice and lower fares overall. My 2 cents.  Mervyn Tan Jui Meng Group Admin and Founder https://www.facebook.com/groups/1013566295436747/

And until Uber stops abusing customers and starts fixing its problems, it is not that company

"The price you see in the app when you enter your pickup and drop off addresses is the rate that you'll be charged for the trip, whether you are matched with a co-rider or taking the trip solo.nThis is the case even if surge pricing is in effect. As it's "partner", I picked up a rider from Breadtalk IHQ at Tai Seng on an UberPOOL trip and sent him all the way home at Punggol, and surprisingly, all I received for fare was $1.41 for a 9km ride, lasting 15mins.   Note: It WASN'T the rider's fault. I did not go on the wrong route, and he DID NOT dispute the fare. It's UBER's superb DYNAMIC fare calculation method.   And upon repeatedly requesting for help via the in-app help button, I finally got a reply from a kind Uber staff named Haydz:   "Thank you for writing in, Valerie.  The fare applied to the trip was the upfront fare. Upfront fares are calculated using the expected time and distance of the trip and local traffic, as well as how many riders and nearby drivers are using Uber at that moment. When fares go up due to increased demand, instead of surge lightning bolts and pop-up screens, riders are given the actual fare before they request their ride.  There‚Äôs no complicated math and no surprises. We estimate the upfront price by considering a variety of factors that typically affect a fare, including surge, traffic, and ERP toll charges. We‚Äôre able to use past data to estimate the likely cost of the trip, and can present that price to a rider before they request.   Let me know if we can help you with anything else."  Thank you Uber, you have helped me made up my mind to return the vehicle to LCR and never to drive for Uber again. Hope fellow Uber "partner" wannabe will take this case into consideration before joining them without doing extensive research.
